---
/**
 * ai-evaluation/0001 · Figure 2 — "Why 'looks good to me' breaks" (vibes vs
 * measured). Copied VERBATIM from the source lesson (figure + svg + figcaption
 * incl. the footnote <sup>); an .astro component, not inline MDX, for the same
 * kebab-case-SVG reason as Fig1.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 640 230"
        role="img"
        aria-label="A reviewer eyeballs five outputs and calls them good; production serves millions, where a small regression hides thousands of bad answers that no human reviews."
    >
        <text x="320" y="18" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >Why &quot;looks good to me&quot; breaks</text
        >

        <!-- vibes side -->
        <rect
            x="30"
            y="40"
            width="270"
            height="150"
            rx="10"
            fill="#fbecec"
            stroke="#9a2417"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="165" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >&#10007; Vibes-based</text
        >
        <text x="165" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >a reviewer reads ~5 outputs</text
        >
        <text x="165" y="95" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >&quot;yeah, looks good&quot; &rarr; ship</text
        >
        <rect x="50" y="108" width="230" height="28" rx="6" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#9a2417"></rect>
        <text x="165" y="126" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#9a2417"
            >no number to compare to last week</text
        >
        <text
            x="165"
            y="156"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="8.5"
            font-style="italic"
            fill="#9a2417">a 3% regression is invisible &mdash;</text
        >
        <text
            x="165"
            y="170"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="8.5"
            font-style="italic"
            fill="#9a2417">and silent across millions of calls</text
        >

        <!-- measured side -->
        <rect
            x="340"
            y="40"
            width="270"
            height="150"
            rx="10"
            fill="#e9f3ec"
            stroke="#2f5d3a"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="475" y="60" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >&#10003; Measured</text
        >
        <text x="475" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >score every change on a golden set</text
        >
        <text x="475" y="95" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >diff vs baseline &rarr; ship or roll back</text
        >
        <rect x="360" y="108" width="230" height="28" rx="6" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#2f5d3a"></rect>
        <text x="475" y="126" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >82% &rarr; 79% = a blocked regression</text
        >
        <text
            x="475"
            y="156"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="8.5"
            font-style="italic"
            fill="#2f5d3a">every change is a before/after diff &mdash;</text
        >
        <text
            x="475"
            y="170"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="8.5"
            font-style="italic"
            fill="#2f5d3a">CI blocks it like a failing test</text
        >

        <text x="320" y="216" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >5 examples fit in a human's head. Millions of calls do not. (numbers illustrative)</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        Eyeballing a handful of outputs works at demo scale and quietly fails in production, where a
        small quality drop is thousands of bad answers nobody reads. Measurement is the only thing
        that scales with traffic.<sup><a href="#s2" id="r2b">2</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
